that
the
increase
in
wind
speed
and
wave
height
identiﬁed
over
the
North
Atlantic
Ocean
could
result
,
at
least
partly
,
from
the
increase
in
greenhouse
gas
concentrations
over
the
last
centuries
.
4.4
.
Consequences
of
these
results
In
addition
to
direct
consequences
on
navigation
,
offshore
engineering
and
even
climate
dynamics
due
to
wave
—
induced
heat
and
mass
ﬂuxes
(
e.g.
,
through
wave
—
induced
turbulence
,
drag
modiﬁcation
and
aerosols
)
,
the
increase
in
H5
in
the
North
Atlantic
Ocean
that
we
demonstrated
in
this
study
has
strong
implications
on
coastal
zone
dynamics
.
Thus
,
the
increase
in
coastal
erosion
observed
in
westem
Europe
over
the
last
century
(
e.g.
Eurosion
,
2003
)
could
be
related
to
the
roughening
of
the
wave
climate
at
northern
latitudes
and
not
only
to
long
—
terrn
sea
—
level
rise
(
Bruun
,
1962
)
and
decrease
in
sediment
supply
from
rivers
due
to
dams
.
This
hypothesis
matches
the
recent
conclusions
of
Ruggiero
(
2013
)
,
who
proposed
that
the
wave
height
increases
in
the
NE
Paciﬁc
have
had
a
more
signiﬁcant
role
in
the
increased
coastal
erosion
than
sea
level
rise
.
To
investigate
this
hypothesis
further
,
one
promising
perspective
would
be
to
force
coastal
area
morphodynamic
models
(
e.g.
besser
et
al.
,
2004
;
Bertin
et
al.
,
2009
)
with
time
series
of
wave
spectra
originating
from
the
hindcast
presented
in
this
study
.
